Kpop Online Survey Participants So Far

Byunghwan Son (bson3@gmu.edu)

01/18/2022

As of January 2, 2022, there are 1,710 participants. Here are some demographic breakdowns. The total of 952 of them are either current US residents or those born in US, which is shown in Figure 1. There were quite a few NA answers herewe want to exclude them from our analysis to be safe.

Figure 1: US Participants

Figure 2: Race/Gender breakdown, US participants

Of the US residents, AAPI people are the relative majority (Figure 2). However, if we combine the Hispanic and non-Hispanic Whites together, it is in fact the Whites who are the majority. Consistent with other surveys, the fan populatio is predominantly female with a sizeable number of non-binary people. Non-White Latinx/Hispanic male fans seem to be very hard to come by.

Figure 3: Race/Gender breakdown, AAPI

Figure 4: Race/Gender breakdown, Korean vs.Non-Korean

I also looked at the detailed makeup of the AAPI people. Three pretty obvious observations:

  • Looking at Figure 3, the AAPI group is REALLY heterogeneous. Not only are there so many different ethnicities, people of mixed Asian heritages are not at all rare.

  • Ethnic Koreans do not make the majority of AAPI. In fact, not even close. If we look at Figure 4, only about about 40 out of 200+ AAPI are of Korean heritage, mixed or otherwise.

  • Male participants of ethnic Koreans are as scarce as those of other ethnicities.

Figure 5: Age Distribution

The distribution of age seems pretty similar across racial groups (Figure 5). But we do have pretty healthy distributions here, meaning that they are not overly concentrated on college-age groups. The distributions of non-White Hispanic and Native Americans might seem a bit different, but thats really the function of a very small number of participants in those categories.

Figure 6: Tulsa Trump Rally Prank

Figure 7: BLM

Looking at the political opinions of Kpop fans in the US, an interesting pattern emerges. When asked about the Tulsa Trump Rally Prank (Figure 6), quite a few people seem to distant themselves from the activists, saying they wouldnt participate in pulling such a prank themselves. A non-negligible number of people also seem to have the position of it doesnt matter to me. When it comes to BLM (Figure 7), however, the great majority of the participants lean supportive of the movement in the name of the Kpop fandom. Ascertaining the reason why would need more analysis, but several possibilities would be:

  1. the word prank has a negative connotation (or signaled the lack of seriousness) and pushed people to be more reserved about it;

  2. social conformity biased might kick in given how widely BLM is accepted;

  3. or people are reluctant to identify with explicitly partisan actions (Tulsa prank).

Another, related, pattern seems to be that the AAPI population seems to be more cautious than others in affirming political activism of the fandom in both cases. Are Asian fans inherently less political than others? AAPI politics literature suggests otherwise, but K-pop fans could be just different from the general population.

As for the attitudes toward the BLM movement, do K-pop fans ideologies play a role here? Figure 9 plots the mean ideology score of US K-pop fans (K-pop fans are generally progressive/liberal as opposed to being conservative) for each category of the fan attitudes toward BLM. Not surprisingly, the fans who strongly espouse fan participation in BLM are likely to be those who view peer K-pop fans as progressive. We are progressives and we should be more involved in BLM in a nutshell. This is a statistically significant difference. For comparison, I also plotted a similar relationship for the Tulsa Prank (8). The result is quite similarthe ones who believe that fans should be more involved in this kind of political actions tend to believe that the fandom is more progressive. Given that there is much weaker overall support for the activism in the Tulsa case, it seems that the attitudinal difference between BLM and Tulsa is not much related to the whether fandom is viewed as progressive (will look into this more at the individual level later).

Note, though, this does not necessarily mean that only those who think K-pop fans are progressive endorse fans involvement in BLM. K-pop-fans in the US in general tend to see their peers as progressive. Those who are ambivalent about Kpop-BLM activism (not affect and respect-but) are not too far off from the average level of ideology score (vertical dashed line). Even the ones who do not approve of the activism (should not engage) still see the overall fandom as progressive (about 6.4) which is not statistically different from those of the ambivalent positions. It can mean many different things, but an immediate implication is that while pro-BLM fans are more likely than others to see the fandom as progressive, a lot of fans who think the fandom is progressive do not endorse the fandoms progressive activism, which can be perhaps a source of individual discontent.

Figure 8: Tulsa Prank and Peer Ideology. Circles are point estimates. Error bars represent the 95% confidence intervals. The vertical dashed line indicates the sample mean of the fan ideology variable.

Figure 9: BLM and Peer Ideology. Circles are point estimates. Error bars represent the 95% confidence intervals. The vertical dashed line indicates the sample mean of the fan ideology variable.

I think theres some behavioralist literature for each of these three. Another thing to note is that there doesnt seem to be much of racial variations here.

Figure 10: K-pop has changed my views of Korea and Koreans in a positive way.

Next, it seems that the median response about whether/how K-pop changed fans views on Korea and Koreans seems to be neutral, though there are quite a few positive answers (Figure 10). Much of this, I think, is attributable to a selection effect: people who had negative views about Korea would be less likely to be K-pop fans in the first place.
